Photo by Alicia Christin Gerald on UnsplashWhen you’re first learning React, you learn that React is “reactive” in a way different from the other frontend frameworks.
The state drives the UI, and that useEffect is the tool designed to watch that state and run code in response.
Suddenly, your brain starts trying to code everything through a state lifecycle.
Suppose, you’re building a form submission, and instead of just sending an API call when the user clicks the button, you think:
“Okay, clicking the button will set a hasSubmitted state to true. Then, I’ll write a useEffect that listens to hasSubmitted, and when it turns true, it will actually trigger the fetch request."
It feels fine at the time. Then a week passes, you open the component to fix a bug, and you find yourself tracing through a weird chain reaction of state updates, conditional statements, and broken dependency arrays just to figure out why a basic button click isn’t working.
If you’ve ever wrapped a click handler in a state variable just to force an effect to run, don’t worry. I made the same mistake. Let’s talk about why we do it, why it turns your code messed up and how to fix it.

What is Wrong With useEffect?
Let’s look at what this actually looks like in practice. Imagine you’re building a simple profile page where a user updates their profile name.
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';function ProfileSettings() {
const [userData, setUserData] = useState({ name: 'Bahadur' });
const [triggerSave, setTriggerSave] = useState(false);
const handleSaveClick = () => {
// The button click handler does nothing but flip a switch
setTriggerSave(true);
};
useEffect(() => {
// The effect watches the switch
if (triggerSave) {
api.updateProfile(userData)
.then(() => {
alert('Saved!');
setTriggerSave(false); // Remember to turn the switch off!
})
.catch(() => setTriggerSave(false));
}
}, [triggerSave, userData]);
return <button onClick={handleSaveClick}>Save Changes</button>;
}
This code works, but it’s incredibly flawed.
Here, you have the managing of the switch. You have to remember to set triggerSave back to false inside both the .then() and the .catch(). If you miss a spot, the button clicks exactly once and then is useless , until the user refreshes the page.

